Here is an example OCaml program that calls an OpenGL compute shader to perform a dot product:

```ocaml
open Gl
open Glu
open Gltypes

let dot_product_shader = 
  "uniform float a[];\n"
  ^ "uniform float b[];\n"
  ^ "layout (local_size_x = 1, local_size_y = 1, local_size_z = 1) in\n"
  ^ "void main()\n"
  ^ "{\n"
  ^ "  float dot = 0.0;\n"
  ^ "  for (int I = 0; I < 4; i++)\n"
  ^ "  {\n"
  ^ "    dot += a[i] * b[i];\n"
  ^ "  }\n"
  ^ "  gl_GlobalInvocationID.x = dot;\n"
  ^ "}\n"

let () =
  glInit ();
  glCreateProgram ();
  glCreateShader glComputeShader;
  glShaderSource (dot_product_shader);
  glCompileShader (dot_product_shader);
  glAttachShader (dot_product_shader);
  glLinkProgram (dot_product_shader);
  glUseProgram (dot_product_shader);
  glDispatchCompute (1, 1, 1);
  glMemoryBarrier glMemoryBarrierAll;
  glReadPixels (0, 0, 1, 1, glRed, glFloat);
  let dot = glReadPixels (0, 0, 1, 1, glRed, glFloat)) in
  Printf.printf "Dot product: %f\n" dot;
  glDeleteProgram (dot_product_shader));
```

This program first initializes the OpenGL context and creates a new program object. It then creates a new compute shader object and sets its source code to the `dot_product_shader` string.

The program then compiles the compute shader, attaches it to the program object, links the program object, and uses the program object.

The program then dispatches a single compute shader invocation, waits for the shader to complete, reads the value of the `gl_GlobalInvocationID.x` variable, which contains the dot product of the two input arrays, and prints the dot product to the console.

Note that this example assumes that the input arrays `a` and `b` are of length 4, and that the output value of the dot product is stored in the `gl_GlobalInvocationID.x` variable. If your input arrays are of different lengths, or if you want to store the output value of the dot product in a different variable, you will need to modify the shader source code accordingly.

