Here's a simple implementation of an RNN using plain TypeScript:

```typescript
class RNN {
  private weights: number[][];
  private biases: number[];

  constructor(inputSize: number, hiddenSize: number) {
    this.weights = [
      new Array(hiddenSize).fill(0), // input to hidden weights
      new Array(inputSize).fill(0), // hidden to input weights
    ];
    this.biases = new Array(hiddenSize).fill(0);
  }

  public forward(input: number[]): number[] {
    const hidden = this.weights[0].map((_, i) => {
      return input.reduce((sum, val, j) => {
        return sum + val * this.weights[0][i][j];
      }, 0) + this.biases[i];
    });
    return hidden;
  }
}
```

This implementation defines an RNN class with two weights matrices and one bias vector. The `forward` method takes an input array and returns the hidden state array.

