Here's an example C# program that sends a POST request with a client certificate attached:

```csharp
using System;
using System.Net;
using System.Security.Cryptography.X509Certificates;

class Program
{
    static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        // Set up the client certificate
        X509Certificate2 clientCert = new X509Certificate2("path/to/client/cert.pfx", "password");

        // Set up the request
        HttpWebRequest request = (HttpWebRequest)WebRequest.Create("https://example.com/api/endpoint");
        request.Method = "POST";
        request.ContentType = "application/json";
        request.ClientCertificates.Add(clientCert);

        // Set up the request body
        string requestBody = "{\"key\":\"value\"}";

        // Send the request
        using (Stream requestStream = request.GetRequestStream())
        {
            byte[] requestBodyBytes = System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(requestBody);
            requestStream.Write(requestBodyBytes, 0, requestBodyBytes.Length);
        }

        // Get the response
        HttpWebResponse response = (HttpWebResponse)request.GetResponse();

        // Read the response body
        using (Stream responseStream = response.GetResponseStream())
        {
            byte[] responseBodyBytes = new byte[response.ContentLength];
            responseStream.Read(responseBodyBytes, 0, response.ContentLength);
            string responseBody = System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetString(responseBodyBytes);
            Console.WriteLine(responseBody);
        }

        // Clean up
        response.Close();
        request.Abort();
    }
}
```

This program sets up a client certificate, sends a POST request with the certificate attached, and reads the response body.

To extract hashtags from text in C#, you can use regular expressions. Here's an example code:

```csharp
using System;
using System.Text.RegularExpressions;

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        string text = "This is a sample text with #hashtags and @mentions.";

        // Regular expression to match hashtags
        Regex regex = new Regex(@"#(\w+)");

        // Find all matches in the text
        MatchCollection matches = regex.Matches(text);

        // Print all hashtags found in the text
        Console.WriteLine("Hashtags found:");
        foreach (Match match in matches)
        {
            Console.WriteLine(match.Groups[1].Value);
        }
    }
}
```

In this example, we use the regular expression `#(\w+)` to match hashtags. The regular expression matches any text that starts with a `#` symbol followed by one or more word characters (letters, digits, and underscores).

We then use the `Regex.Matches()` method to find all matches of the regular expression in the input text.

Finally, we loop through all matches and print out the hashtag text (excluding the `#` symbol) using the `Match.Groups[1].Value` property.

